{"summary":"Three amendments identify concrete correctness or corruption defects in the filesystem task-run handling. The remaining amendment is a design objection to the chosen replay/repair strategy, not a demonstrated bug.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-15-03ed3b3d","decision":"accept","rationale":"`record_task_run_start` can create two open runless attempts for the same bead/project when the only existing running row has a different `started_at`. `update_task_run` and `record_bead_completion` do not use `started_at` to disambiguate, so a later completion with `run_id=None` hits the ambiguous-open-match path and fails. That means the API can create runless state that its own runless completion path cannot reliably finalize."},{"amendment_id":"fr-15-ad53be55","decision":"accept","rationale":"The per-milestone write lock lives under `milestones/<id>/mutation.lock`, and `AdvisoryFileLock::acquire` creates the parent directory before any milestone existence check. A typoed write against a nonexistent milestone therefore leaves behind an empty milestone directory plus lock file. After that, `milestone_exists` reports the directory as corrupt because `milestone.toml` is missing, which blocks normal creation until manual cleanup."},{"amendment_id":"fr-15-967d37de","decision":"accept","rationale":"`read_task_runs_from_path` checks JSON syntax but never checks that each row's `milestone_id` matches the milestone file being read. Downstream reconciliation and `find_runs_for_bead` then trust those rows without revalidating, so a misfiled entry can affect the wrong milestone's active/progress state or appear in the wrong audit output instead of surfacing corruption immediately."},{"amendment_id":"fr-15-ed0d03f2","decision":"reject","rationale":"The cited logic is permissive, but this amendment does not demonstrate a concrete correctness, safety, or robustness failure caused by that permissiveness. The code intentionally supports idempotent replay and partial-write repair, while still rejecting conflicting terminal updates and conflicting metadata. On technical merit, that is a design tradeoff rather than a proven defect."}]}